pr_review_comment_body:
On Tue, May 10, 2016 at 12:21:28PM -0700, pbrunet wrote:
> > @@ -176,6 +179,17 @@ namespace pythonic
> >        {
> >          return {_base._value};
> >        }
> > +#ifdef USE_BOOST_SIMD
> > +      using simd_iterator = const_broadcast_iterator<decltype(_base._splated)>;
> > +      simd_iterator vbegin() const
> > +      {
> > +        return {_base._splated};
> > +      }
> > +      simd_iterator vend() const
> > +      {
> > +        return {_base._splated};
> > +      }
> > +#endif
> 
> I don't get it.
It's hacky : this iterator always returns the same value and cannot
advance, or be compared to the end...

Now I remembered that I checked that during my preliminary research, and I did a manual check just now to double confirm that, for the following sample model definition where the 2 members share the same `blobType` shape, they will end up as 2 different shape instances despite they are with the same type. So there would be no problem when we later use `if self._context.get('streaming_shape') == shape`.

            'shapes': {
                'OperationNameResponse': {
                    'type': 'structure',
                    'members': {
                        "Blob": {'shape': 'blobType'},
                        "Body": {'shape': 'blobType'}
                    },
                    'payload': 'Body'
                },
                'blobType': {
                    'type': 'blob'
                }
            }

So, no need to worry. It is a good question. Thanks!

What about returning a proxy object so we don't have to create the app context twice?

```
class LazyMinter(object):
    def __init__(self, value):
    # or even __init__(self, ctx, param, value):
        self.name = value
    @cached_property
    def minter(self):
        try:
            return current_pidstore.minters[value]
        except KeyError:
            raise click.BadParameter(
                param_hint='minter',
                message='Unknown minter {0}. Please use one of: {1}.'.format(
                    value, ', '.join(current_pidstore.minters.keys())
                )
            )

    def __call__(self, *args, **kwargs):
        return self.minter(*args, **kwargs)
```

Nit: Why not just this?

```  def __body_parameter_descriptor(self, method_id):
    return {
        'name': 'body',
        'in': 'body',
        'schema': {
            '$ref': '#/definitions/{0}'.format(
                self.__request_schema[method_id])
        }
    }
```

@Jelleas it's a Python 3.6 thing on all Macs, not dependent on older versions of OSX:

https://bugs.python.org/issue29065
https://bugs.python.org/issue29480

Since Engine can be optional when specifying DBSnapshotIdentifier, perhaps this could be coded:
```
        if 'DBSnapshotIdentifier' not in self.properties:
            if 'Engine' not in self.properties:
                raise ValueError(
                    'Resource Engine required in type %s' % self.resource_type)```

basically, you need this code in this if block:
```
      task_spec *spec = task_task_spec(worker->task_in_progress);
      /* Return dynamic resources back for the task in progress. */
      for (int i = 0; i < MAX_RESOURCE_INDEX; i++) {
        state->dynamic_resources[i] += task_spec_get_required_resource(spec, i);
        /* Sanity-check resource vector boundary conditions. */
        CHECK(state->dynamic_resources[i] <= state->static_resources[i]);
      }
```

@dzhulgakov 
Thanks. 
By using `std::unordered_set`, it will not be a problem anymore.

it will make sense to make this block contingent on getting a valid result from `w_realpath` so that the realpath call can catch the real ENOENT and we can distinguish between that and a bad casing problem.

```
if (watch_path) {
   struct stat st;
   w_stat(..)
}
```
